{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626776"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:41:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:41:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17093"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17093"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.06,0,0.03,0.85]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9783"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77021"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9783"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17093"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62527"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5112"},{"type":"tags","id":"10203"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23115"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77021"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBisphosphonates are commonly prescribed medications that affect bone metabolism. They are structurally similar to pyrophosphate, a natural regulator of bone mineralisation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of bisphosphonates?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enhances parathyroid hormone secretion","Stimulates osteoblast differentiation","Promotes vitamin D activation","Increases calcium absorption in the intestine","Inhibits osteoclast-mediated bone resorption"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBisphosphonates primarily work through \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibition of osteoclast-mediated bone resorption\u003C/strong\u003E. They bind to hydroxyapatite in bone and are taken up by osteoclasts during bone resorption. Inside osteoclasts, they inhibit the mevalonate pathway which is essential for osteoclast function, leading to reduced bone breakdown.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhancement of parathyroid hormone secretion\u003C/strong\u003E: bisphosphonates do not directly influence parathyroid hormone production or secretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulation of osteoblast differentiation\u003C/strong\u003E: while there may be minor indirect effects on osteoblasts through coupling mechanisms, bisphosphonates do not primarily act by stimulating bone formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromotion of vitamin D activation\u003C/strong\u003E: bisphosphonates have no direct effect on vitamin D metabolism or its activation pathways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased calcium absorption in the intestine\u003C/strong\u003E: bisphosphonates do not affect intestinal calcium absorption; this is primarily regulated by vitamin D and parathyroid hormone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe strong binding of bisphosphonates to bone mineral gives them specific targeting to skeletal tissue. This property, combined with their inhibition of osteoclast function, makes them effective treatments for conditions involving excessive bone resorption such as osteoporosis, Paget disease, and malignant hypercalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bisphosphonates work by inhibiting osteoclast-mediated bone resorption through disruption of the mevalonate pathway.","Bisphosphonates bind strongly to hydroxyapatite in bone tissue, giving them specific targeting to skeletal tissue.","The primary clinical uses of bisphosphonates are in treating osteoporosis, Paget disease, and malignant hypercalcaemia."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62527"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17093"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62527"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:32:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:33:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9783"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77021"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"upda